Part I - San Francisco Bay Area Ford GoBike Sharing Data¶

by Derrick Narkah¶

Introduction¶

The Ford GoBike System Data is data collected on 183413 individual rides made in a bike-sharing program in the San Francisco Bay Area covering the period of February 2019.

Data Assessment¶

  1. Remove null values since they make up about only 5% of the dataset ((8265+197)/183413)
  2. Change datatypes (start_station_id, end_station_id, bike_id to strings), (member_birth_year to int) & (member_gender, user_type,bike_share_for_all_trip to category)
  3. One member was born in 1878. This is practically impossible as the person would have been 149 years old as at 2019. This is a typo and should be changed to 1978.

# Converting start_station_id, end_station_id and bike_id to strings
ids = ['start_station_id','end_station_id','bike_id']

for i in ids:
   
    gobike[i] = gobike[i].astype('str').str[:-2]
In [13]:
# Converting member_birth_year to integer so the decimal is removed.
gobike['member_birth_year'] = gobike['member_birth_year'].astype(int)
gobike['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(gobike['start_time'])
gobike['end_time'] = pd.to_datetime(gobike['end_time'])
In [14]:
# Converting member_gender, user_type, bike_share_for_all_trip to category
ordinal_var_dict = {'member_gender': ['Male','Female','Other'],
                    'user_type': ['Customer', 'Subscriber'],
                    'bike_share_for_all_trip': ['No', 'Yes']}

for var in ordinal_var_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,
                                                categories = ordinal_var_dict[var])
    gobike[var] = gobike[var].astype(ordered_var)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

After assessing and cleaning the data, we now have 174952 bike rides on ford gobike system for February 2019.

The data collected include the duration of the bike usage, the start and end times, the start station id and station name as well as the end station id and station name. The longitude and latitudes of the locations. Also captured as the bike ids, user type, member birth year, gender and bike share for all members.

Almost all data columns need no further explanation with the exception of the user type and Bike_share_for_all.

The user_type captures whether the user is a Customer (One who uses the system when needed but has not signed up for any membership deal)or a Subscriber (one who has a monthly or annual membership deal with ford gobike). Ford GoBike provides discounted annual memberships to qualifying low-income Bay Area residents. These are the Bike_share_for_all beneficiaries.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out relationships and insights concerning the GoBike Stations that will inform the company on where to focus in:

  1. Improvements to the gobike system
  2. Advertisements
  3. Best factors to consider when scaling up the system to other areas

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I suspect the categorical data and station locations given will support my investigation.

From the bar plot above, it can be seen that there were GoBike rides on each single day of the month of February but these rides varied for all the days. The last day of the month (Feb 28) recorded the highest number of rides as (Feb 13) recorded the lowest number of rides.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

In exploring the categorical values, it was realised that the data was very skewed to specific categories. Examaple. There was a huge difference in the number of Subscribers and Customers. Same could be said about the Genders and Bike share For All Discount members. No transformations were done.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The first plot, which is not exactly a Univariate plot but was needed to provide the first overview of the data had some grouping done to be able to plot the number of rides according to the days of the month.

Some Data Assessment and Cleaning was done prior to the initial investigations. Aside these, no adjustment of the data was performed for the Univariate plots.

This plot shows that people in their 30's took the most rides in February followed by those in their 20's. The combined number of rides for these two age groups was more than the rest of the age groups. It seems a bit interesting the number of rides taken by young adolescents and teenagers (10-19) is very low.

The preceeding plot showed the number of rides compared with the various age groups. This scatter plot here shows the duration of rides compared among the various age groups. A large number of rides were less than 10000 secs (approximately 3 hours) hence the very dense portion of the scatter plot. Some of the longest ride durations were taken by the 20-40 age group. The older the people got, the less time they spent riding. This plot buttresses the earlier one.

The subsequent plots showed that the Stations where rides started from the most also had rides ending there the most. These were the most active stations and could be considered the hot zones for GoBike ride patronage. More bikes could be invested in these areas to avoid shortage. The converse is also true. For those further away, they will need a lot more reason to use the GoBike system unless some consideration in the cost is made for them.

Third if the interest of the other genders could be raised, the patronage will increase. Men contributed the highest in the usage of the GoBike system and while it may seem explainable, the numbers of females once increased, will directly improve the usage.

# Importing geodesic for calculation of distance between two points given the latitudes and longitudes.
from geopy.distance import geodesic
In [56]:
# Get the latitude and longitude rows and return the calculated distance with the geodesic method and save in new dataframe column
def distancer(row):
    coords_1 = (row['start_station_latitude'], row['start_station_longitude'])
    coords_2 = (row['end_station_latitude'], row['end_station_longitude'])
    return geodesic(coords_1, coords_2).km

gobike_top7['distance_km'] = gobike_top7.apply(distancer, axis=1)

Conclusions¶

From the February 2019 dataset investigated, It was realised that the GoBike System is used alot. More Users have subscribed to an annual membership plan. Among these, more men use the service. 20-40 year olds take the most rides and undertake rides that cover the longest distances. Certain Stations can be considered hot spots ie. that is they have more rides starting from them and ending there as well. Rides from these stations did not necessarily cover the most distances.

These points realised from the exploration of the dataset could help in fine tuning advertisement and upscaling the GoBike System and where to invest more resources

Limitation of this Exploration

Additional data on the counties where the stations are located and data gathered from other areas could provide more insight and support or refute some of the claims made here
